{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-bd4e04bf4b7118f4", "type": "tool_result", "content": "tle attention to the efficiency of reasoning in spoken language models. Our work fills this gap by bringing efficient reasoning ideas, particularly curriculum-based compression, into the SLM setting. 3. Method 3.1. ECoM Reasoning Framework Efficient Chain-of-Modality Reasoning ( ECoM Reasoning ) is built upon the Chain-of-Modality (CoM) architecture (Fig. 1 ). By compressing the textual component, it enables text to jointly serve as speech guidance and a carrier of core reasoning, thereby reducing inference cost. 3.1.1. Chain of Modality. For clarity of exposition, we describe our method in the setting of a single-turn multimodal dialogue. Let S S denote the system prompt, X s X^{s} the user speech input, and Y s Y^{s} the assistant speech response. Our goal is to model the posterior distribution of the assistant speech response conditioned on the available user inputs and the system prompt, i.e., P ​ ( Y s ∣ X s , S ) P(Y^{s}\\mid X^{s},S) . To explicitly incorporate structured reasoning, we introduce the intermediate textual variables X t X^{t} and Y t Y^{t} , where X t X^{t} denotes the transcript of the user speech X s X^{s} , and Y t Y^{t} represents the assistant’s textual response before speech generation. Then we can expand the posterior as (1) P ​ ( Y s ∣ X s , S ) \\displaystyle P(Y^{s}\\mid X^{s},S) = ∑ X t , Y t P ​ ( Y s , Y t , X t ∣ X s , S ) \\displaystyle=\\sum_{X^{t},Y^{t}}P(Y^{s},Y^{t},X^{t}\\mid X^{s},S) = ∑ X t , Y t [ P ( Y s ∣ Y t , X t , X s , S ) \\displaystyle=\\sum_{X^{t},Y^{t}}\\bigg[P(Y^{s}\\mid Y^{t},X^{t},X^{s},S)\\, ⋅ P ( Y t ∣ X t , X s , S ) ⋅ P ( X t ∣ X s , S ) ] . \\displaystyle\\cdot P(Y^{t}\\mid X^{t},X^{s},S)\\,\\cdot P(X^{t}\\mid X^{s},S)\\bigg]. Since exact marginalization is intractable in practice, we adopt a Viterbi-style approximation: (2) P ​ ( Y s ∣ X s , S ) ≈ P ​ ( Y s ∣ Y ^ t , X ^ t , X s , S ) , P(Y^{s}\\mid X^{s},S)\\approx P(Y^{s}\\mid\\hat{Y}^{t},\\hat{X}^{t},X^{s},S), where (3) X ^ t = arg ⁡ max X t ⁡ P ​ ( X t ∣ X s , S ) , \\displaystyle\\hat{X}^{t}=\\arg\\max_{X^{t}}P(X^{t}\\mid X^{s},S), Y ^ t = arg ⁡ max Y t ⁡ P ​ ( Y t ∣ X ^ t , X s , S ) . \\displaystyle\\hat{Y}^{t}=\\arg\\max_{Y^{t}}P(Y^{t}\\mid\\hat{X}^{t},X^{s},S). Under this approximation, the model first predicts a textual representation of the user input, then generates the assistant text conditioned on it, and finally produces the assistant speech. In other words, given input speech X s X^{s} , the interaction process can be modeled as a sequential generation chain X s → X t → Y t → Y s X^{s}\\rightarrow X^{t}\\rightarrow Y^{t}\\rightarrow Y^{s} (as shown in Fig. 1 (a)), which is the standard CoM (Zhang et al. , 2023 ) . (4) standard CoM : [ S ] [ X s ] → [ X t ] [ Y t ] [ Y s ] . \\textsc{standard CoM}:\\quad[S]\\,[X^{s}]\\;\\rightarrow\\;[X^{t}]\\,[Y^{t}]\\,[Y^{s}]. where each part is separated by a special token. This paradigm has been shown to provide both semantic coherence and high-quality synthesized speech (Zhang et al. , 2024 ; Arora et al. , 2025a , b ) , and it naturally extends to multi-turn settings by conditioning on the dialogue history and applying the same response generation process at each turn. To further enable explicit reasoning, we introduce an additional intermediate textual variable R t R^{t} , which represents the model’s reasoning process prior to response generation. The posterior can then be approximated as (5) P ​ ( Y s ∣ X s , S ) ≈ P ​ ( Y s ∣ Y ^ t , R ^ t , X ^ t , X s , S ) , P(Y^{s}\\mid X^{s},S)\\approx P(Y^{s}\\mid\\hat{Y}^{t},\\hat{R}^{t},\\hat{X}^{t},X^{s},S), where (6) X ^ t \\displaystyle\\hat{X}^{t} = arg ⁡ max X t ⁡ P ​ ( X t ∣ X s , S ) , \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{X^{t}}P(X^{t}\\mid X^{s},S), R ^ t \\displaystyle\\hat{R}^{t} = arg ⁡ max R t ⁡ P ​ ( R t ∣ X ^ t , X s , S ) , \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{R^{t}}P(R^{t}\\mid\\hat{X}^{t},X^{s},S), Y ^ t \\displaystyle\\hat{Y}^{t} = arg ⁡ max Y t ⁡ P ​ ( Y t ∣ R ^ t , X ^ t , X s , S ) . \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{Y^{t}}P(Y^{t}\\mid\\hat{R}^{t},\\hat{X}^{t},X^{s},S). Under this formulation, the model first transcribes the user speech into text, then generates an intermediate reasoning trace, next produces the final textual response conditioned on that reasoning, and finally synthesizes the assistant speech, yielding the following generation chain: (7) CoM Reasoning : [ S ] [ X s ] → [ X t ] [ R t ] [ Y t ] [ Y s ] . \\textsc{CoM Reasoning}:\\quad[S]\\,[X^{s}]\\;\\rightarrow\\;[X^{t}]\\,[R^{t}]\\,[Y^{t}]\\,[Y^{s}]. 3.1.2. Compressed Data Construction. To enable reasoning without increasing the overall text-token inference cost, we compress the intermediate user text X t X^{t} at the sentence level and compress R t R^{t} at the token level according to a predefined compression ratio. The compressed reasoning representation is denoted by R ~ t \\tilde{R}^{t} . Sentence-level compression of X t X^{t} . For the intermediate user text X t X^{t} , we adopt an aggressive sentence-level compression. Specifically, the entire user text with its surrounding special tokens is removed from the training sequence. This design is motivated by our empirical finding that progressive training enables the model to retain strong speech understanding ability regardless of whether reasoning is included, even when X t X^{t} is fully removed from the output sequence. Token-level compression of R t R^{t} . For the reasoning text R t R^{t} , we apply token-level compression. Specifically, we first compute an importance score for each reasoning token, and then retain only a certain proportion of the most important tokens while removing the rest, producing a shorter compressed reasoning sequence R ~ t \\tilde{R}^{t} . We adopt this relatively conservative strategy because we observe that fully removing R t R^{t} causes a much larger degradation in performance than full reasoning, while selective token preservation better balances reasoning effectiveness and inference efficiency. To estimate token importance, we adopt LLMLingua-2 (Pan et al. , 2024 ) as the token-importance scorer, following TokenSkip (Xia et al. , 2025 ) . We choose this method because it does not require any modification to the underlying LLM architecture, and can achieve a higher reduction rate of the reasoning steps (Sui et al. , 2025 ) . Specifically, given an input token sequence x ≤ n = ( x 1 , … , x n ) x_{\\leq n}=(x_{1},\\ldots,x_{n}) , we feed the full sequence into LLMLingua-2 (the parameters are denoted as θ MB \\theta_{\\mathrm{MB}} ) and the importance of the i i -th token x i x_{i} is calculated as (8) I 2 ​ ( x i ) = P ​ ( x i ∣ x ≤ n ; θ MB ) , I_{2}(x_{i})=P(x_{i}\\mid x_{\\leq n};\\theta_{\\mathrm{MB}}), Here, I 2 ​ ( x i ) I_{2}(x_{i}) reflects the estimated importance of token x i x_{i} conditioned on the entire input sequence, since LLMLingua-2 is trained as a token-level classifier with supervision derived from token-importance annotations. We then use these scores to retain high-importance tokens and remove less informative ones during compression. To verify that this token-level compression strategy is suitable for our data, we manually sampled and inspected compressed examples from our dataset. We provide representative cases on the project page, which show that the method preserves the key reasoning content well after compression. In summary, by applying compression at both the sentence level and the token level, we construct the training data for the compressed reasoning model. An example of this data construction process is shown in Table 1 . Within the training setup described in Section 4.1 , this compression procedure is applied to the mathematical reasoning data to create compressed reasoning supervision, whereas the general dialogue data is used in its original form for spoken dialogue training. Table 1 . Example of compressed data construction. <u_t> , <r_t> , and <a_t> are special tokens indicating the user text, reasoning text, and assistant text segments, respectively, and <eot> marks the end of a segment. Compression Example Sequence Full sequence “ <u_t> If I have two apples and buy one more, how many apples do I have? <eot> <r_t> The user asks a simple counting question. Start with two apples and add one more. <eot> <a_t> You have three apples. <eot> ” Compress X t X^{t} “ <r_t> The user asks a simple counting question. Start with two apples and add one more. <eot> <a_t> You have three apples. <eot> ” Compress R t R^{t} “ <r_t> two apples one more <eot> <a_t> You have three apples. <eot> ” 3.1.3. Efficient Chain-of-Modality Reasoning. After compressed data construction, we provide a compact approximation to the same posterior objective while requiring fewer generated tokens: (9) P ​ ( Y s ∣ X s , S ) ≈ P ​ ( Y s ∣ Y ^ t , R ~ ^ t , X s , S ) , P(Y^{s}\\mid X^{s},S)\\approx P(Y^{s}\\mid\\hat{Y}^{t},\\hat{\\tilde{R}}^{t},X^{s},S), where (10) R ~ ^ t \\displaystyle\\hat{\\tilde{R}}^{t} = arg ⁡ max R ~ t ⁡ P ​ ( R ~ t ∣ X s , S ) , \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{\\tilde{R}^{t}}P(\\tilde{R}^{t}\\mid X^{s},S), Y ^ t \\displaystyle\\hat{Y}^{t} = arg ⁡ max Y t ⁡ P ​ ( Y t ∣ R ~ ^ t , X s , S ) . \\displaystyle=\\arg\\max_{Y^{t}}P(Y^{t}\\mid\\hat{\\tilde{R}}^{t},X^{s},S). Compared with explicitly modeling X t X^{t} and R t R^{t} , this formulation preserves the essential reasoning signal while improving token efficiency. Based on the probabilistic formulation above, we provide the sequence realization: (11) ECoM Reasoning : [ S ] [ X s ] → [ R ~ t ] [ Y t ] [ Y s ] , \\textsc{ECoM Reasoning}:\\quad[S]\\,[X^{s}]\\;\\rightarrow\\;[\\tilde{R}^{t}]\\,[Y^{t}]\\,[Y^{s}], 3.2. Progressive Training Pipeline Figure 2 . Overview of the proposed progressive training pipeline for ECoM Reasoning . The model is trained in three stages, transitioning from standard speech interaction to full-form reasoning supervision and finally to compressed reasoning. Directly training ECoM Reasoning is difficult because the model must simultaneously learn speech interaction and compressed textual reasoning. Such joint optimization is highly challenging for the backbone model, especially when the compressed text is expected to both support speech generation and carry the essential reasoning process. To address this issue, we adopt a curriculum-style progressive training strategy that moves from easier objectives to harder ones. As shown in Fig. 2 , the proposed pipeline consists of three stages: Standard CoM , CoM Reasoning , and ECoM Reasoning . Stage 1: Standard CoM We first train the model in the standard CoM setting on speech dialogue and spoken question answering datasets that do not contain explicit reasoning supervision, allowing the model to acquire the basic ability to understand spoken input and generate spoken output. Stage 2: CoM Reasoning We then introduce a CoM Reasoning stage with explicit supervision over the full-form intermediate reasoning chain. At this stage, training data includes full reasoning traces, which help the model learn the complete reasoning process before compression is introduced. Stage 3: ECoM Reasoning Finally, we transition to ECoM Reasoning , where the full intermediate text is replaced by a compact reasoning representation. This enables the model to preserve reasoning capability while reducing the cost of text-token generation at inference time. In summary, the progressive pipeline first builds fundamental speech interaction ability, then injects explicit reasoning supervision, and finally distills this capability into a more efficient compressed-text reasoning format. 4. Experiments 4.1. Experimental Setup Training Setting. We use two categories of training data: general dialogue data for developing the model’s spoken dialogue ability, and mathematical reasoning data for enhancing its reasoning capability on math-intensive tasks. For general dialogue training, we use MagpiePro (Xu et al. , 2024 ) and InfGen (Li et al. , 2025a ) , with speech synthesized by CosyVoice3 (Du et al. , 2025 ) , following DrVoice (Tan et al. , 2025a ) and Fun-Audio-Chat (Team et al. , 2025 ) . We keep only single-turn dialogue examples and discard samples with combined speech and text token length exceeding 4K. After filtering, the resulting dialogue corpus contains 12.7K hours of speech. For mathematical reasoning training, we use GSM8K (Cobbe et al. , 2021 ) , NuminaMath (Li et al. , 2024 ) , and MathQA (Amini et al. , 2019 ) . To ensure that each sample contains an explicit reasoning process, we keep only samples with question , solution , and answer fields, thereby excluding proof-style problems and other samples without step-by-step solutions. We then synthesize speech using GPT-4o-mini-TTS (Hurst et al. , 2024 ) . The resulting math reasoning corpus contains 206,216 samples in total, corresponding to 1.5K hours of synthesized speech. Our training framework is built on top of SLAM-LLM (Ma et al. , 2026 ) , as it provides a unified and modular foundation for speech-language modeling, naturally supporting the integration of speech encoding, intermediate text/reasoning generation, and speech decoding in our framework. The SLM used in our experiments consists of a Whisper encoder (Radford et al. , 2023 ) , a CosyVoice 3 decoder (Du et al. , 2025 ) , and Qwen2.5-1.5B (Team, 2024 ; Yang et al. , 2024 ) . In addition, following SLAM-Omni (Chen et al. , 2025b ) , we adopt group modeling for speech-token decoding, which reduces the effective length of speech token sequences and improves decoding efficiency. Evaluation Setting. We evaluate our method on both reasoning and non-reasoning benchmarks. Our primary evaluation focuses on reasoning tasks. To this end, we consider four math reasoning datasets: AddSub (Hosseini et al. , 2014 ) , SingleEq (Koncel-Kedziorski et al. , 2015 ) , MultiArith (Roy and Roth, 2015 ) , and SVAMP (Patel et al. , 2021 ) , which are widely used to assess the mathematical reasoning ability of LLMs. The questions and answers in these datasets are of moderate difficulty and can be naturally expressed in speech, making them suitable for evaluating SLMs of moderate scale. For spoken response evaluation, we use the same complete evaluation set as STITCH (Chiang et al. , 2025b ) , including the synthesized speech items. In addition, we evaluate general spoken dialogue ability using a subset of non-reasoning test sets selected from UltraEval-Audio (Shi et al. , 2026 ) . These test sets include Llama Questions (Nachmani et al. , 2023 ) , a knowledge-oriented generated-speech dataset. All experiments are conducted under the URO-Bench and UltraEval-Audio evaluation frameworks. 4.2. Main Results Table 2 . Results on math question benchmarks. We report accuracy (%) ↑ \\uparrow , the average number of generated text tokens (#Tok) ↓ \\downarrow , and token efficiency (Acc/#Tok) ↑ \\uparrow . The best result in each column is shown in bold . Model AddSub MultiArith SingleEq SVAMP Average Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Cascade 53.21 72.48 0.73 58.04 111.82 0.52 61.16 78.56 0.78 48.82 109.58 0.45 55.31 93.11 0.62 standard CoM 46.78 166.04 0.28 43.67 188.18 0.23 34.55 159.30 0.22 33.33 203.01 0.16 39.58 179.13 0.22 CoM Reasoning 48.62 100.85 0.48 63.40 95.41 0.66 72.78 86.92 0.84 46.15 103.07 0.45 57.74 96.56 0.61 w/ budget = 20 21.10 29.86 0.71 0.57 33.00 0.02 26.91 30.15 0.89 10.81 29.36 0.37 14.85 30.59 0.50 w/ budget = 30 50.15 41.10 1.22 5.17 39.48 0.13 40.06 40.44 0.99 23.29 39.61 0.59 29.67 40.16 0.73 ECoM Reasoning 52.59 31.92 1.65 71.83 31.05 2.31 75.84 26.02 2.91 42.36 31.86 1.33 60.66 30.21 2.05 Table 3 . Ablation on the reasoning-text 