{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-844e434b627edd78", "type": "tool_result", "content": " , 40 % 40\\% , 20 % 20\\% , and 0 % 0\\% of its original length, and train/evaluate all models under the same configuration. Table 3 reports the results. We find that a compression ratio of 40 % 40\\% achieves the best overall performance, yielding the highest response accuracy and high token efficiency. Interestingly, although the 0 % 0\\% setting attains the highest token efficiency, its response accuracy drops substantially, indicating that it is not the optimal choice. This also suggests that the Acc/#Tok metric has limitations as a measure of efficiency, since a higher value does not necessarily correspond to better overall reasoning quality. This finding indicates that the original reasoning text contains substantial redundancy. Moderate compression removes non-essential tokens while preserving the core reasoning process, whereas insufficient compression retains unnecessary token cost and excessive compression risks discarding useful reasoning information. Table 4 presents a representative example. The full-form reasoning ( 100 % 100\\% ) is verbose but correct, while compressed variants at 80 % 80\\% , 60 % 60\\% and 40 % 40\\% preserve only the key arithmetic structure and still lead to the correct answer. However, the 20 % 20\\% setting produces an incorrect intermediate reasoning path and thus yields a wrong answer, suggesting that excessive compression can lead to reasoning errors. Overall, these results support the use of moderate reasoning compression in ECoM Reasoning . Table 4 . Example of reasoning-text compression under different compression ratios. Question: “A bookstore had 41 books in the bargain bin. If they sold 33 books but then put 2 more in the bin, how many books would be in the bin?” Ratio Predict Text Answer CoM Reasoning A bookstore had 41 books in the back room. If they sold 33 books but then put 2 more in the bin, how many books would be in the bin? The bookstore had 41 − 33 = 8 41-33=8 books left in the back room. After putting 2 more in the bin, there would be 8 + 2 = 10 8+2=10 books in the bin. The answer is 10. 10 ECoM Reasoning 100% The number of books in the bin is 41 − 33 = 8 41-33=8 books. After adding 2 books, the number of books in the bin is 8 + 2 = 10 8+2=10 books. The answer is 10. 10 80% bargain bin 41 − 33 = 8 41-33=8 books. Adding 2 books, bin 8 + 2 = 10 8+2=10 books. The answer is 10. 10 60% bookstore sold 33 books 41 − 33 = 8 41-33=8 books put 2 books 8 + 2 = 10 8+2=10 books. The answer is 10. 10 40% bookstore sold 33, 41 − 33 = 8 41-33=8 , put 2, 8 + 2 = 10 8+2=10 . The answer is 10. 10 20% 41 33 74 2 76 41\\;\\;33\\;\\;74\\;\\;2\\;\\;76 . The answer is 76. 76 0% The answer is 10. 10 Why can moderate compression improve answer accuracy? Simply having a longer thought process does not guarantee improved results (Balachandran et al. , 2025 ) . One possible explanation is that unconstrained reasoning often contains substantial redundancy, and excessively long generated sequences are more susceptible to distraction and error accumulation (Sang et al. , 2026 ) . In contrast, concise reasoning may offer a cleaner and more effective signal for prediction. 4.3.2. Impact of Training Strategy Table 5 . Ablation on progressive training strategies for ECoM Reasoning . We report accuracy (%) ↑ \\uparrow , the average number of generated text tokens (#Tok) ↓ \\downarrow , and token efficiency (Acc/#Tok) ↑ \\uparrow . The best result in each column is shown in bold . Strategy AddSub MultiArith SingleEq SVAMP Average Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow One-stage 36.69 76.14 0.48 11.30 35.64 0.32 37.61 9.50 3.96 23.85 9.19 2.60 27.36 32.62 1.84 Two-stage 35.47 25.59 1.39 50.38 28.76 1.75 61.46 26.87 2.29 37.23 29.50 1.26 46.14 27.68 1.67 Three-stage (reversed) 53.51 28.16 1.90 53.44 28.32 1.89 63.60 27.23 2.34 41.80 30.87 1.35 53.09 28.65 1.87 Four-stage 57.49 28.17 2.04 61.49 29.18 2.11 69.41 26.87 2.58 38.23 29.86 1.28 56.66 28.52 2.00 Three-stage (ours) 52.59 31.92 1.65 71.83 31.05 2.31 75.84 26.02 2.91 42.36 31.86 1.33 60.66 30.21 2.05 We further ablate the progressive training strategy by comparing several alternative training schedules for ECoM Reasoning . Specifically, we evaluate: (1) a one-stage setting that directly trains ECoM Reasoning from scratch; (2) a two-stage setting that trains CoM first and then directly transitions to ECoM Reasoning ; (3) a three-stage variant with reversed compression order, where compressed reasoning is introduced before removing the user text; and (4) a four-stage setting that separately compresses the user text and the reasoning text in two successive stages. To ensure a fair comparison, we keep the remaining training hyperparameters unchanged across all settings, including the initial learning rate, total training steps, and batch size, despite the different numbers of stages. The results are reported in Table 5 . Our default three-stage strategy consistently achieves the best response accuracy, suggesting that it provides the most effective curriculum for transferring the benefits of textual guidance and explicit reasoning into the compressed format. By comparison, fewer training stages reduce token usage during generation but lead to inferior reasoning performance, indicating insufficient adaptation to the compressed representation. In contrast, the four-stage strategy brings no further improvement and may introduce a greater risk of overfitting. 4.3.3. Performance on Non-reasoning SpeechQA For non-reasoning tasks, we trained the ECoM interaction architecture without explicit reasoning, following the same progressive compression principle, whose format is (12) ECoM : [ S ] [ X s ] → [ X t ] [ Y t ] [ Y s ] ⇒ [ Y t ] [ Y s ] . \\textsc{ECoM}:\\quad[S]\\,[X^{s}]\\;\\rightarrow\\;[X^{t}]\\,[Y^{t}]\\,[Y^{s}]\\;\\Rightarrow\\;[Y^{t}]\\,[Y^{s}]. And we compare three settings: CoM , directly trained ECoM , and progressively trained ECoM . As shown in Table 6 , CoM attains slightly better response accuracy, while the progressively trained ECoM model achieves much higher token efficiency. This suggests that compressed intermediate text can retain most of the useful guidance for knowledge-based speechQA while significantly reducing the cost of text generation. Table 6 . Results on the No-reasoning SpeechQA. We report accuracy (%) ↑ \\uparrow , the average number of generated text tokens (#Tok) ↓ \\downarrow , and token efficiency (Acc/#Tok) ↑ \\uparrow . Model w/o reasoning LlamaQ Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow Acc/#Tok ↑ \\uparrow standard CoM 56.00 153.21 0.37 ECoM (direct) 49.66 84.95 0.58 ECoM (progressive) 52.66 80.68 0.65 Why does progressive training help? We perform a case study to analyze the mechanism behind progressive training. Specifically, we compare two ECoM models: one trained directly from scratch and one trained progressively, starting from an initial CoM stage. For the same input instance, we examine token-level generation and measure the similarity between the last-layer hidden states of the ECoM model and those of a CoM model at the corresponding token positions. The corresponding results are shown in Fig. 3(a) . ECoM -progressive exhibits consistently higher similarity than ECoM -direct across all 29 layers (average gain of 0.058 0.058 ), with non-overlapping 95% confidence intervals. This indicates that progressive training enables the model to better capture the full textual generation chain before transitioning to the compressed format. Consequently, although the final generated text is compressed, the associated hidden representations still preserve information from the original full-form text sequence. 4.3.4. Impact of Compressing Assistant Text (a) Layer-wise hidden-state similarity to CoM on Llama Questions. ECoM -progressive shows consistently higher similarity than ECoM -direct across all 29 layers, with non-overlapping 95% confidence intervals. (b) Accuracy under different retained ratios when compressing the assistant text Y t Y^{t} on Llama Questions. We compare models trained with compressed Y t Y^{t} and an original model evaluated with inference-only compression. Figure 3 . Case studies on progressive training and assistant-text compression. Why is the assistant text Y t Y^{t} not compressed? We observe that, unlike X t X^{t} and R t R^{t} , the assistant text Y t Y^{t} is highly sensitive to compression. To study this effect, we evaluate two scenarios across different retained ratios of Y t Y^{t} : (1) a model trained and evaluated with compressed assistant text, and (2) an original model for which Y t Y^{t} is compressed only at inference time. The results are presented in Fig. 3(b) . Notably, if compressed Y t Y^{t} remained sufficient for recovering the full speech response, then the inference-only compression setting should still allow the model to produce competitive speech outputs. In practice, however, both settings suffer clear degradation in speech accuracy as the retained ratio decreases, with especially severe deterioration at aggressive compression levels. This shows that Y t Y^{t} is not merely a redundant textual byproduct, but a crucial intermediate representation that is tightly coupled with downstream speech generation. Therefore, while compressing user text and reasoning text is effective, finding a lossless compression strategy for assistant text remains an open problem. 4.3.5. Impact of Different Architectures Why do we adopt the CoM-based architecture? Using the general dialogue training data, the same backbone and training configurations, we pre-train three end-to-end variants: Parallel , Interleave , and standard CoM without reasoning, and compare them with the cascade system built from the same backbone components. Results on the LLaMA Questions benchmark show that standard CoM achieves 56.00% accuracy, substantially outperforming Interleave (45.67%) and Parallel (38.33%). Moreover, the pre-trained CoM model approaches the cascade system, which reaches 60.33% accuracy. In addition, our method requires inserting relatively long reasoning spans before the final assistant response, which is poorly suited to the generation patterns of Interleave and Parallel . By contrast, CoM naturally accommodates such structured insertion. Therefore, we use CoM as the backbone architecture throughout this work. 5. Limitations ECoM Reasoning improves the reasoning efficiency of spoken language models without increasing inference cost, but several limitations remain. First, similar to the Chain-of-Modality ( CoM ) architecture, ECoM Reasoning has high time-to-first-speech-token latency. Since the model needs to generate the text response before generating the speech response, the initial speech delay can be larger than parallel and interleaved text-speech interaction frameworks. However, ECoM Reasoning remains valuable in scenarios where answer accuracy is more important than instant response, such as spoken mathematical question answering, educational tutoring, and other tasks involving careful multi-step reasoning. Second, we do not evaluate ECoM Reasoning on larger-scale models, so its scalability to stronger backbones remains unverified. Nevertheless, results on the 1.5B model already provide strong evidence of its potential, suggesting that compact reasoning representations and Progressive Compression are promising for improving reasoning efficiency in SLMs. Third, our study is limited to English and does not evaluate cross-lingual or multilingual settings. We leave multilingual and cross-lingual evaluation as important future work. 6. Conclusion We introduce ECoM Reasoning , to our knowledge, the first framework that incorporates compressed textual reasoning into spoken language models. The key idea is to rethink the role of intermediate text in SLMs: rather than serving only as a scaffold for speech generation, it can be compressed into an efficient representation that also carries the core reasoning process. Built on the CoM architecture, this design enables better use of the text-token budget without increasing inference cost. To make such a representation learnable, we further propose a progressive compression strategy that gradually bridges full-form reasoning and compact reasoning. We believe this opens a new and promising avenue for future research on more intelligent spoken language models. Acknowledgements. This work was supported by National Natural Science Foundation of China (No. U23B2018), the Science and Technology Innovation (STI) 2030-Major Project (2022ZD0208700), Yangtze River Delta Science and Technology Innovation Community Joint Research Project (2024CSJGG1100), and Alibaba Research Intern Program. References L. AI (2025) LFM2 technical report . arXiv preprint arXiv:2511.23404 . Cited by: Appendix F . A. Amini, S. Gabriel, S. Lin, R. Koncel-Kedziorski, Y. Choi, and H. Hajishirzi (2019) Mathqa: towards interpretable math word problem solving with operation-based formalisms . In Proceedings of the 2019 Conference of the North American Chapter of the Association for Computational Linguistics: Human Language Technologies, Volume 1 (Long and Short Papers) , pp. 2357–2367 . Cited by: §4.1 . S. Arora, J. Tian, H. Futami, J. Jung, J. Shi, Y. Kashiwagi, E. Tsunoo, and S. Watanabe (2025a) Chain-of-thought training for open e2e spoken dialogue systems . arXiv preprint arXiv:2506.00722 . Cited by: §1 , §1 , §3.1.1 . S. Arora, J. Tian, H. Futami, J. Shi, Y. Kashiwagi, E. Tsunoo, and S. Watanabe (2025b) Chain-of-thought reasoning in streaming full-duplex end-to-end spoken dialogue systems . arXiv preprint arXiv:2510.02066 . Ci