 trained with a batch size of 2 per GPU for 2 epochs (each epoch approximately 63,900 steps), using a learning rate of 1 × 10 − 5 1\\times 10^{-5} . We used a warmup-and-cosine decay schedule with 3,000 warmup steps and 300,000 total training steps. Validation was performed every 6,390 steps with a 1% split, so that 10 checkpoints corresponded to one epoch. The speech encoder was frozen during training, while the LLM remained trainable. Table 7. Training configuration used in our experiments. Setting Value Hardware 4 × \\times NVIDIA A800 GPUs Distributed Training DDP ( torchrun ) Precision FP16 PEFT Disabled LLM Backbone Qwen2.5-1.5B LLM Hidden Size 1536 Speech Encoder Whisper-Small Encoder Hidden Size 768 Input Feature 80-bin mel-spectrogram Audio Code Type CosyVoice 3 Group Decoding Enabled Group Size 3 Group Decode Adapter Linear Batch Size / GPU 2 Effective Batch Size 8 Epochs 2 Learning Rate 1 × 10 − 5 1\\times 10^{-5} Warmup Steps 3000 Max Steps 300000 Validation Interval 6390 steps Validation Split 0.01 Encoder Freeze Yes Appendix B Prompt Configuration We use the same system prompt for all subsets to maintain a simple and consistent training setup and to facilitate fair comparisons across experiments. System Prompt: Conduct a spoken conversation with the user. Appendix C Evaluation Configuration As a supplement to Section 4.1, Table 8 summarizes the evaluation configuration. All results were obtained using a unified test-time template, and the same decoding settings were applied across experiments to ensure fair comparisons. For decoding, we used deterministic generation with a text repetition penalty of 1.0 and an audio repetition penalty of 1.2, which helps reduce silence. The maximum generation length was set to 9000 tokens. The audio prompt was fixed to the default tone for all evaluations. Table 8. Unified evaluation configuration used in all experiments. Setting Value Test Split test Dataset Version speech-to-speech Random Seed 888 Text Repetition Penalty 1.0 Audio Repetition Penalty 1.2 Max New Tokens 9000 Sampling Disabled Output Text Only False Speech Sample Rate 24000 Online Inference Disabled Audio Prompt default_tone Appendix D Case Studies We provide audio-annotated case studies from the main experiments and ablation studies on the project page for further inspection. Table 9 . Comparison of efficient-reasoning methods. #Eff: Acc/#Tok Method AddSub MultiArith SingleEq SVAMP Average Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow #Eff ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow #Eff ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow #Eff ↑ \\uparrow Acc ↑ \\uparrow #Tok ↓ \\downarrow #Eff ↑ \\uparrow ECoM Reasoning(Ours) 52.59 31.92 1.65 71.83 31.05 2.31 75.84 26.02 2.91 42.36 31.86 1.33 60.66 30.21 2.05 LLMLingua-1 48.01 61.16 0.78 73.94 55.25 1.34 76.14 48.62 1.57 40.80 60.96 0.67 59.72 56.50 1.09 LongLLMLingua 46.78 61.00 0.77 70.49 53.44 1.32 69.72 47.11 1.48 42.02 59.68 0.70 57.25 55.31 1.07 Chain-of-Draft 41.28 56.02 0.74 66.47 54.82 1.21 53.82 45.57 1.18 34.11 57.77 0.59 48.92 53.55 0.93 Cold-Stop 36.08 33.41 1.08 14.55 34.00 0.43 38.53 30.76 1.25 28.98 30.47 0.95 29.54 32.16 0.93 Stepwise Internalisation 39.44 9.52 4.14 10.34 9.00 1.15 49.23 9.43 5.22 27.31 9.00 3.03 31.58 9.24 3.39 Heima 35.77 11.83 3.02 8.62 11.00 0.78 50.76 11.33 4.48 29.20 11.00 2.65 31.09 11.29 2.74 Table 10 . Speech synthesis quality on the four math-QA benchmarks. Method AddSub MultiArith SingleEq SVAMP Average WER % ↓ \\%\\downarrow UTMOS ↑ \\uparrow WER % ↓ \\%\\downarrow UTMOS ↑ \\uparrow WER % ↓ \\%\\downarrow UTMOS ↑ \\uparrow WER % ↓ \\%\\downarrow UTMOS ↑ \\uparrow WER % ↓ \\%\\downarrow UTMOS ↑ \\uparrow LFM2-Audio 11.04 4.11 12.68 4.13 13.09 4.13 0 9.75 4.15 11.64 4.13 Cascade 17.94 4.14 12.47 4.21 0 8.93 4.24 11.04 4.20 12.60 4.20 CoM 19.46 4.37 10.52 4.37 14.80 4.38 13.65 4.32 14.61 4.36 CoM Reasoning 13.79 4.25 11.37 4.18 10.14 4.22 10.03 4.22 11.33 4.22 ECoM Reasoning 14.14 4.17 10.40 4.13 0 7.43 4.12 0 9.53 4.15 10.38 4.14 Appendix E Other Efficient-reasoning Methods Broader comparisons would help provide a more comprehensive assessment of our method. In addition to the budget-constrained baseline reported in the main paper, we further re-implemented several representative efficient-reasoning methods using the same backbone and training setting. These include LLMLingua-1 (Jiang and others, 2023 ) and LongLLMLingua (Jiang and others, 2024 ) , which use token-level importance scoring as a drop-in replacement for our LLMLingua-2 scorer on the reasoning text R t R^{t} ; Chain-of-Draft (Xu et al. , 2025b ) and Cold-Stop (proposed in (Zhang et al. , 2025b ) ), which use prompts or model-entropy signals, respectively, to guide early exiting from the reasoning trace to the answer span without additional training; and Stepwise Internalisation (Deng et al. , 2024 ) and Heima (Shen and others, 2025 ) , which distill the reasoning process into latent states or special tokens through curriculum learning. Since none of these methods has been previously applied to SLMs, all implementations were adapted by ourselves and may therefore differ from the original works in certain hyperparameter choices and implementation details. As shown in Table 9 , our method remains competitive among these extended baselines. In particular, implicit-CoT methods (Deng et al. , 2024 ; Shen and others, 2025 ) compress the reasoning process more aggressively and thus achieve higher token efficiency, but at the cost of lower accuracy. The advantage of our method stems from more accurate selection of key reasoning tokens than (Jiang and others, 2023 , 2024 ) , stronger training–inference consistency than (Xu et al. , 2025b ; Zhang et al. , 2025b ) , and better preservation of intermediate reasoning signals than (Deng et al. , 2024 ; Shen and others, 2025 ) . Appendix F Speech-quality evaluation Although the main focus of this work is the correctness of spoken answers under a constrained token budget, speech naturalness is also important. We evaluate speech quality using two metrics: WER (between the assistant text and speech) and UTMOS . For context, we also report results for an open-source 1.5B SLM, LFM2-Audio-1.5B (AI, 2025 ) , and for a cascade system. As shown in Table 10 , ECoM Reasoning shows only a small drop in UTMOS (4.14), which is also close to the reported human speech score on LibriSpeech-PC (4.09) (Chen and others, 2025 ) , suggesting limited impact on speech generation quality. Appendix G AI Usage Statement AI-based tools were used only for language polishing and proofreading. They were not used for experimental design, data processing, model development, result analysis, or scientific content generation. All technical contributions and conclusions are the responsibility of the authors. Experimental support, please view the build logs for errors. Generated by L A T E xml . Instructions for reporting errors We are continuing to improve HTML versions of papers, and your feedback helps enhance accessibility and mobile support. To report errors in the HTML that will help us improve conversion and rendering, choose any of the methods listed below: Click the \"Report Issue\" ( ) button, located in the page header. Tip: You can select the relevant text first, to include it in your report. Our team has already identified the following issues . We appreciate your time reviewing and reporting rendering errors we may not have found yet. Your efforts will help us improve the HTML versions for all readers, because disability should not be a barrier to accessing research. Thank you for your continued support in championing open access for all. Have a free development cycle? Help support accessibility at arXiv! Our collaborators at LaTeXML maintain a list of packages that need conversion , and welcome developer contributions . We gratefully acknowledge support from our major funders , member institutions , , and all contributors. About &m